commitResults.messageTitle: Update DeveloperGuide.md use case for listing TAs
Modify search (find) command to include prefixes
commitResults.messageBody:
Current find command by default only searches the keyword(s)
in persons' names.

This design does not offer much extensibility of the command function.
User is not able to search for keywords contained in other fields apart
from the persons' names. Keyword(s) are split and searched word by word
if there are any white spaces present, thus user cannot indicate he/she
would like multiple keywords to be contained in specified sequence.

Let's modify the find command with the following prefixes
and implementation changes:
* add the prefix 'k/' before every keyword
* add the prefix 'f/' before the field (e.g. name)
* more than one keyword can be entered but must be separated by 'k/'
* do not split each keyword string by white space - each keyword can
  contain multiple words.

This implementation of the find command will allow for future
extensibility so that user can eventually search for keyword(s)
across all fields.

commitResults.messageBody:
Current find command is only able to search for keyword(s) in
persons' names.

This limits the ability for a user to search across all fields or
to specify any other fields apart from `name`.

Let's create:
* an abstract class ContainsKeywordsPredicate.java.
* predicate subclasses for each of the fields. Each subclass will
  extend from the ContainsKeywordsPredicate superclass.
* Test cases to test functionality of executing the find command
  with each separate field.

commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the default list is loaded from the json file.
There is no functionality to reorder this list.

User is not able to organise the list in a specific numerical
or alphabetical order.

Let's create a new sort command, which parses in the field
that the user wants to sort the candidate list by. The list
will order candidates based on the in-built java comparator
on the particular field.

There are currently no test cases for the sort command.

This causes code lines relevant to the sort command implementation
to be left unchecked, and thus the code coverage is less than
the required threshold.

Let's add a SortCommandParserTest class with test cases to
check for invalid fields in the user input, empty user input,
as well as 'successful' test cases.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update schedule command to check for candidate availability
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the schedule command does not check whether the user's
input for interview datetime matches the candidate's availability.

This allows interviews to be set for candidates on days that
the candidates are not available. Instead, this should be invalid
and should throw an error.

Let's implement checks to ensure the interview datetime matches the
candidate's availabilities. A new method through the
ModelManager and InterviewSchedule class will return true if the
interview datetime matches the candidate's availability, and false
otherwise. The schedule command will throw an error message if
there is no match.

Enhance view command to specify time period
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the view command only allows the user to view
all scheduled interviews.

The user is not able to filter the interview schedule by
time period.

Let's enhance the view command with three time period
keywords: 'today', 'week' and 'month', to display
scheduled interviews within the time period from when the
command is entered. Let's also modify the implementation
of InterviewSchedule related methods in the ModelManager
so that the interviews will be sorted from the earliest
to latest interview slot in the UI panel.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add test cases for classes that relate to execution of view command
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, test cases relevant to the existing view command are out
of date due to modification to the view command accepted
user input format.

This causes an error when the test cases compile. No test cases are
present for the new ViewCommandParser class and Predicate classes.

Let's create more test cases to test the functionality of view
command to ensure it ouputs results we expect. In summary, this
includes:
* updates to test cases in ViewCommandTest class
* new ViewCommandParserTest class
* new WithinTimePeriodPredicate test classes
Due to the time sensitive input of view command, the ViewCommandTest
class is only able to check for the new ViewCommand object,
but is not able to handle an equality check.

Note: Slight implementation change to predicate subcless for
WithinTimePeriodPredicate to check that the interview date time
is later than the current date time.

Modify accessor and constructor for predicate classes
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the abstract class inherited by the predicate subclasses
has a private accessor for its variable.

This prevents subclasses from accessing the variable from its
methods. Results in unecessary code in subclasses to create its own
variable to instantiate.

Let's modify the accessor in the abstract parent class to protected
instead of private.

Fix implementation of find command for candidate field
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the find command searches for all fields under
each candidate via the candidate.toString() method.

This causes the search to include irrelevant strings e.g.
"availability" and "phone". This also results in edge cases
where find k/availability f/candidate will bring up positive
search results.

Let's fix the implementation in the CandidateContainsKeywordsPredicate
class so that the find command will separately check through each
of the candidate's fields and return through if any of these
fields include any of the keywords.

Note: Small edit to Seniority class and predicate class to
enable the find command to search according to the text that
the candidate card in the gui displays, i.e. COM1, COM2 etc.

* headers for each panel to indicate each panel's use
* larger default window size for the gui app
* extend the feedback box to have a larger minimum height

commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, there is no command or functionality
for the user to record a remark for each candidate.

This means that the user is not able to record certain
points relating to each candidate.

Let's extend the command class to create a RemarkCommand.
The implementation follows similarly to the tutorial
for adding a command. The remark command is implemented as a
standalone command, i.e. any replacement of a candidate's
remark has to be done via the remark command user input.

Allow InterviewStatus to be triggered by Scheduling - Currently the InterviewStatus has to be triggered manually - In this iteration, the InterviewStatus will be triggered when a user schedules an interview - With this, the InterviewStatus will not be able to be edited manually in this iteration as well.
